My Gloriosum lost 3 leaves and has not been growing!

So let’s transfer her to Leca! -Stay tune for updates🌿

I’ve learned to love Leca over the past 2 years and I find it easier to maintain. 

What is Leca?

Leca stands for Lightweight expanded clay
aggregate. Clay balls that can absorb some
water making it ideal for a plant medium.

I love Leca because is easier for me to water, i can keep an eye on the roots. With leca you can use self-water pots. I have been using just regular glass/plastic containers and I just make sure that the water a bit higher than usual when I first transfer them. 

If you use Leca you must provide Nutrients!

Unlike soil, Leca does not provide nutrients so you will need to add your favorite nutrients to your water when watering your plants in Leca.

Thrips are the worst! 🌿

When I first found them on my plants I had nothing to treat them with so I made same mix  that use to treat spider mites. Now this mix won’t let rid of thrips (that I’ve heard) but it will definitely slow them down in the meantime.Today is day 4 of me repeating this treatment daily and I haven’t noticed them back (yet). 

The mix :
1 part water
1 part rubbing alcohol 
Few drops of dish soap 

I ordered systemic plant insecticide and Captain Jacks Deadbug and will treat them with the systemic mix as soon as I get them in the mail! 

Since thrips are annoying and the can also be in the soil if I still notice them by next week I will be repotting these plants to be safe and keep on treating them! Thrips won’t win this fight! 

How do you treat your plants for pests?

Let’s help each other out in the comments🌿

Why are there plugs plants?

Plugs are used to grow seedlings inside a mesh plug for ease of transportation and transplanting.

Roots are “supposed” to grow through the mesh but in most cases roots get trapped in this mesh plug not allowing it to fully grow out and eventually suffocating and killing the plant.

This Thai had a pretty good root system that managed to grow through the mesh and some that were already damaged by the plug. When taking the mesh you have to very careful that roots don’t come off with it😖

Excited to see how she does in Leca 🥹

Simple ways to help those plant babies 🌱

1. Making sure the new leaf path is clear. So that the new leaf can open freely. I’ve had so many leaves damaged just because it was growing through something or against something 😭

2. Clean the leaves! You can use whichever solution you like to clean the leaves. I make a mixture of 3 part water 1 part rubbing alcohol and a few drops of dish soap. 

3. I like to make sure that those moss poles are somewhat moist to encourage the aerial roots to grow. 

4. Keep an eye on those leaves who tend to get stuck! Provide extra humidity.

5. Stop procrastinating and water that poor plant that’s been staring at you for the past two 

6.Follow the last one at your own risk…

Gloriosum Glow Up 🌱✨

She was looking rough last year! Leca saved the day! 

Aside from using leca as a permanent medium for some of my plants, I use it to help the plants that are struggling. Whenever I have a plant whose roots are dry or rotten I use leca to develop a healthy root system. In this case once there was a healthy root system stablished I repotted her back into soil. I let this gloriosum grow in leca for over 8 months. 

She had 2 leaves and a 3rd on the way when I decided to put her in soil. Now this baby is pushing a 4th leaf 🥹

Leaf sprout for my friend’s headphones! 🌱

@vhsynl asked me and I delivered haha! 

I tried my best to write down the patter! Hopefully this helps!

Chain 10
1 Sc 
1 Hdc
2 Dc 
 1 Tc 
1 hdc
2 dc
1sc 
Sl st 

Flip can do the same on the other side of the chain 
1 Sc 
1 Hdc
2 Dc 
 1 Tc 
1 hdc
2 dc
1sc 
Sl st 

After you have completed the other side chain 10 and repeat the patter. When you’re done with the second leaf Sl st into the center all the way to the other side of the leaf.  At the end leave a long tail to tie it to the headphones!
